post_text: We're so proud of you Susan!! What a great moment to share. George Deans is a fantastic instructor.
shared_text:
Susan Dickson-Smith
May 27 at 5:52 PM ·

I made a woodworking breakthrough today. I've been frustrated for years by my inability to cut a board square. I made a great bench hook in my RSU 24 Adult Education woodworking class, which has helped me make good straight cuts, but the hope has always been that I'd eventually make straight cuts freehand.

I started out with nine boards to cut. I used the bench hook for the first three...then I started the next couple of cuts with the bench hook, then finished the cut freehand. For the last four cuts, I made the whole cut freehand.

I knew-because my teacher explained it- that I'd have to learn to lock my arm and elbow in a single plane, but today, I felt it actually happen.

Yes, I could have cut all this lumber in 20 minutes or less with a chop saw, but I wouldn't have this sense of satisfaction and achievement.

Thanks to my wonderful teacher, George Deans, and to RSU 24 Adult Education for making this proud moment possible.

#handtoolwoodworking #handtoolsonly #coopbuild #oldschoolyardfarm

MEOC.MAINE.EDU
MEOC is now offering Virtual Services! | Maine Educational Opportunity Center

Maine Educational Opportunity Center
April 28 at 2:55 PM ·

The Maine Educational Opportunity Center works with Maine adults to help them go to college. With remote classes and a hurting economy, the college climate in Maine is changing pretty fast! MEOC is here to help you figure things out.

As part of our efforts to work with our participants remotely, MEOC is now offering virtual services. This can happen in a few different ways, including email, text, Zoom, and more!

To apply online, or register for one of our virtual sessions, please check out the Virtual Services page on our website.

https://meoc.maine.edu/sessions/virtual-services/

April 7 at 6:12 PM ·

Sometimes I have to entertain myself. I have limited myself to only leaving the house to deliver essentials. No one said what I had to wear to deliver those essentials. When Brown's Appliances and Stanley Subaru donated the van, they didn’t know how important it would become to keep doing what we do. I have turned the van into our “Mobile Essentials Unit” (still playing with the name.) We have things like bags of beef stew, cereal, hamburger helper meals, raviolis, canned veggies, formula (some brands), ramen, soap, and more. If you find yourself going without anything to eat. Message me. I can meet you or if you are in my delivery area, I can drop it off. I am doing the zero contact during my deliveries.

Even those of us who are familiar with online video conferencing are learning a new skill set with the seemingly overnight migration of our entire program to online learning and teaching.

Fortunately, we have some pretty amazing technology resources available to us. The trick is learning what those tools are and the best ways to utilize them. Also, which resources work best in various situations.

This is a good article comparing two highly used video conferencing platforms: Google Hangouts and Zoom Meetings.

What platform works best for you? Do you have any tips you can pass on?

January 14 at 4:55 PM ·

There are five places left in Heidi Eagleton's Reiki I class coming up this weekend!

The word Reiki is made of two Japanese words - Rei which means "God's Wisdom or the Higher Power" and Ki which is "life force energy". So Reiki is actually "spiritually guided life force energy." Come and align yourself with this healing energy. It is not massage and no touching of a body is needed to do Reiki on another person who is fully clothed. Both classes are needed to complete Reiki Level 1. Class size is limited. Please bring something to drink and your lunch.

post_text:
Meet our new team member, Dell Hambleton.

Dell is our new Ed Tech, which means she'll be supporting the Adult Ed program in a number of ways from working with students and supporting program instructors, to teaching courses on meditation, photography, and personal finance. She holds a master's degree in Adult Education from Oregon State University, and a bachelor's degree in journalism from Humboldt State University.

Dell is a former newspaper reporter and photojournalist. She’s worked as a career readiness counselor and business coach, and currently as an instructional designer, tutor, substitute teacher, hospice volunteer, seamstress and quilter.

We've also noticed that she has the perfect way to curate pencils and pens, so if you happen to need one, you'll know who to ask. Welcome Dell!

post_text:
Thinking about college?
Shelbie Ross from the Maine Education Opportunities Center will be at the Sullivan Town Hall Thursday (Feb. 14 ♥️)from 2-4pm to help break down the steps you need to reach your goal. She's an excellent resource to tap on subjects such as entrance requirements, admission procedures, and FINANCIAL AID! To register, call 1-800-281-3703.
